ra></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>The latest revision to the public transport fare formula is a clear departure from formulae Singapore has relied on thus far to ensure bus and train fares are equitable to all.</Para><Para>This is somewhat puzzling.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>Firstly, there is the matter of directly linking fares to cost - not only operating cost, but the cost of building up our public transport network. This flies in the face of a longstanding principle of not allowing such costs to trickle down to commuters, so as to instil efficiency among operators, and financial prudence in the Government.</Para><Para>The quality of public transport determines the attractiveness of the city to residents and foreign investors alike.</Para><Para>Which is why governments in many jurisdictions see it in their interest to subsidise bus and train services heavily. This philosophy is even more relevant in Singapore, where up to two-thirds of residents - quite likely, more in future - cannot afford a car.</Para><Para>The very reason why our public transport is the least expensive among developed cities could be correlated to why our cars are the most expensive.</Para><Para>Secondly, the issue of transparency. The new formula is for the first time, opaque. Components such as inflation, wage, energy and productivity - which have been in use in past fare formulae - are easy to understand and easily accessible to the public.</Para><Para>The most contentious part remains this: that the council has conceded to the argument that the cost of building up Singapore's public transport system has got to be recovered from commuters.</Para><Para>But the new "network capacity factor" (NCF) is anything but. It is a formula within a formula, and made up of obscure terms such as "operated train place kilometre" and "passenger kilometre".</Para><Para>Even if one is able to work out these equations, obtaining the relevant figures would be difficult. Such numbers are not publicly available.</Para><Para>The Public Transport Council, which announced the revised formula yesterday, would not even give a hint of what some of these numbers look like. Neither would the council say how fares would have been affected if the new formula had been in place last year.</Para><Para>This is uncharacteristic of the council, which has thus far been quite transparent.</Para><Para>The fare watchdog would say only that the NCF hinges on the growth of our public transport network vis-a-vis growth in commuter demand. For instance, if the network capacity outpaces growth in demand, the NCF number would be a positive. And if demand growth outstrips growth in network capacity, the NCF number would be negative.</Para><Para>How large this number can be is anyone's guess.</Para><Para>The third point has to do with lost opportunity. In this case, the council missed an excellent chance to introduce a service standard component into the formula.</Para><Para>While the NCF can be perceived as a proxy to service - because the more capacity there is, the more accessible and comfortable a mode of transport becomes - the relationship is vague and tenuous. Sheer capacity may not translate directly to service improvement, as it does not take into account breakdowns and delays.</Para><Para>The recipe would have been so much more palatable if it had been framed differently. Instead of the NCF, why not use a factor based on reliability measures we have now? These figures are publicly available and are a good gauge of service standards.</Para><Para>But the most contentious part remains this: that the council has conceded to the argument that the cost of building up Singapore's public transport system has got to be recovered from commuters.</Para><Para>This cost-recovery thinking is misplaced in the public transport sphere, where the benefits - in terms of productivity and staying car-lite - extend far beyond a positive balance sheet.</Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">Christopher Tan </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field"></Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">(c) 2018 Singapore Press Holdings Limited </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item></AdocTOC></DistDoc>

